{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491293","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491293"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:41:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:41:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"906"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/906"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.33,0.21,0.15,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"906"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90283"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/906"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"906"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74536"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"175"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"291"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30955"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90283"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 60-year-old man is taken to the Emergency Department following an unwitnessed, unconscious collapse. He has been unwell for the last four days with diarrhoea, abdominal discomfort, and poor oral intake. On examination his pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60mmHg, and respiratory rate 22/min. His overall condition improves considerable after intravenous fluid resuscitation. A bedside ultrasound is performed and shows a previously undiagnosed 48 mm abdominal aortic aneurysm, with no evidence of leakage or rupture. There is no free peritoneal fluid. No other abnormalities are found.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following most accurately reflects the 5-year rate of rupture of this abdominal aortic aneurysm?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1%","5%","10%","20%","50%"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe risk of rupture of an abdominal aortic aneurysm of this 48 mm size is less than \u003Cstrong\u003E1%\u003C/strong\u003E. However and more importantly, the rate of growth is an important factor in considering the risk of rupture. An increase in rate of growth of an aneurysm of any diameter of more than 0.5 cm in six month merits consideration of repair. This patient will need regular surveillance. An aneurysm greater than 5.5cm warrants repair, provided the risk of surgery does not outweigh the risk of rupture. Abdominal symptoms in a patient with a known or incidentally found aortic aneurysm requires consideration of whether the aneurysm is the cause of the symptoms or not.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abdominal aortic aneurysms \u003C50 mm in diameter have a very low risk of rupture over a 5-year period."],"references":["Kent KC. Abdominal Aortic Aneurysms. N Engl J Med 2014; 371:2101-8."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74536"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"906"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74536"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-13T16:03:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-13T16:03:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"906"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90283"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"21","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/21"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb5","name":"Vascular